{
  "name": "11265-mcp-add-server-bypass",
  "target_process": "warp-oss",
  "_purpose": "Reproduction evidence for warpdotdev/warp#11265. Runs against a warp-oss binary built WITH DEMO-PATCH-B + DEMO-PATCH-C (so SECRETS_REGEX compiles on toggle and parse_templatable_json scans raw JSON before from_user_json templatization) but WITHOUT DEMO-PATCH-C-NEW (no raw-input scan inside the new-server save branch of handle_action). The recipe proves: with secret redaction visibly ON, a NEW server save via '+ Add' that embeds a secret in the top-level url is silently accepted (BUG), while the SAME secret saved via edit-existing on a previously-added server is correctly blocked (control). The bug is that the new-server save branch calls ParsedTemplatableMCPServerResult::from_user_json directly, skipping parse_templatable_json (which is where the predicate is wired).",
  "_safety": "Token is the deterministic placeholder `sk-FAKE0000000000FAKEdemoWARP11265`. Matches the Generic SK regex from custom_secret_regex_list.",
  "_state_touched": "Adds MCP entries `demo-baseline-11265` (no secret, Phase C control) and `demo-add-bypass-11265` (the bug save) to MY MCPS. Phase E uses edit-existing on demo-baseline-11265; that save is BLOCKED so MY MCPS retains exactly the two entries from Phases C and D. Ends with the toggle ON.",
  "_phases": [
    "A: open Settings, search 'redaction'; confirm toggle starts OFF",
    "B: click toggle ON; wait for 'Secret visual redaction mode' dropdown",
    "C: navigate to MCP Servers \u2192 + Add \u2192 paste a NON-secret baseline config (demo-baseline-11265) \u2192 Save \u2192 expect it to land in MY MCPS (establishes a server to edit later)",
    "D: navigate back to MCP Servers \u2192 + Add \u2192 paste config with sk- in url \u2192 Save \u2192 expect demo-add-bypass-11265 to land in MY MCPS (BUG: should have been blocked; +Add bypasses parse_templatable_json)"
  ],
